bibdata.title: Replace ISO 639 gem with one that includes ISO 639-3
Indexing updates for ISO 639-3 three-letter codes

comments.body:
Some possible gems:

* https://github.com/bbenno/languages -- it does not currently include macrolanguages and has not yet had a version 1.0.0 release, but does have CI and a nice script for updating the code data. Update: it now includes macrolanguages.
* https://github.com/mlj/iso-codes -- on version 1.2.0, tests but no CI, does include macrolanguages

We could also forego using an additional gem, and use the [debian iso-codes package](https://packages.debian.org/sid/iso-codes) or [the tables directly from SIL](https://iso639-3.sil.org/code_tables/download_tables).
I don't see the CSS?

@cwulfman I didn't include any CSS — the above produces a collapsible/expandable menu with pure HTML. But if we want to have the styling look more like the current site, I believe we can use CSS to e.g., customize the bullets, etc. to do that.

Generate report for any and all Cotsen Items within the Digital Repository

comments.body:
I ran the report like this, and gave the output to Kim:

```ruby
docs = Blacklight.default_index.connection.get("select", params: {qt: "search", fl: "id, imported_location_tesim", qf: "imported_location_tes
im", "q.alt": "imported_location_tesim:(CTSN CTSNRF HSVC XC RCPXC SCACTSN SCAHSVC XCR)", defType: "edismax", rows: 10000})["response"]["docs"].map{|x| x["id"]
}.lazy.map{|x| ChangeSetPersister.default.query_service.find_by(id: x)}
report = CSVReport.new(docs, fields: ImportedMetadata.fields)
report.write(path: Rails.root.join("tmp", "report.csv"))
```

It's not pretty, but it's literally every field Figgy knows how to import or manages itself.

pulfalight.title: Query string on Collection page results in 500 server error

comments.body:
This may be due to bots crawling the site since it occurs frequently on one day every few months. It's unclear if this is intended behavior. It's also unclear as to why the query string is there as it does not seem to be related to any Pulfalight features.

Honeybadger Title: [PULFALight/production] NoMethodError: undefined method `except' for "1":String

This happens frequently. It looks like the `[]` characters in the query string date range are to blame here. If we replace this snippet:
```
range[solr_year_i][begin][]=1850&range[solr_year_i][end][]=1899
```
With this snippet:
```
range[solr_year_i][begin]=1850&range[solr_year_i][end]=1899
```
It then works as expected.
